<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Textures and Painting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to select, preview, and paint ground textures onto the map grid.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Selecting a World
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Before painting textures, you need to select a
        <Bold>world number</Bold> . This number
        corresponds to a texture folder in the game's directory structure
        (
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">server\textures\worldX\</Run> ) and
        determines which set of ground textures are available for painting. It also loads the
        matching
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">style.tma</Run> file, which
        defines the texture styles used by building facets.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        To get started, open the
        <Bold>Textures</Bold> tab in the editor drawer and type a world
        number into the
        <Bold>World</Bold> box. Once entered, the canvas will populate with the
        default texture for that world and the texture palette will load. In the examples below,
        we use
        <Bold>World 3</Bold> .
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/textures_world_selected.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Custom Worlds:</Run>
                <Run>World numbers 0–20 are reserved for the game's built-in texture sets.
Custom worlds use numbers</Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">21 and above.</Run>
                <Run>To create a custom world, open the</Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Style Editor</Run>
                <Run>and define a new style with a world number of 21 or higher. Save the style
from within the Style Editor — the Map Editor will then be able to read it immediately,
allowing you to select that world number in the World box and paint with your custom textures.
When you are ready to test in-game, use the Style Editor's</Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Export</Run>
                <Run>function to write the style files to the game's textures folder. The engine
will then load the custom world exactly like any built-in world.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        The Texture Palette
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The texture palette is divided into three tabs, each containing a different category
        of textures:
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">World Textures</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Textures unique to the selected world number, corresponding to
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">tex000hi</Run> through
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">tex255hi</Run> .
        These vary between worlds and typically include terrain, building facades, rooftops,
        and other environment-specific surfaces.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Shared Textures</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Textures available to every world number, corresponding to
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">tex256hi</Run> through
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">tex511hi</Run> .
        These are common assets used across all levels -- sidewalks, roads, walkways, kerbs,
        fence graphics, and other universal surfaces.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Prims Textures</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Textures normally reserved for 3D prim objects. The engine does allow
        these to be painted onto ground cells, though this is not their primary purpose. They can
        be useful for adding unique detail to specific areas of a map.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,16,0,4">
        Beta Textures
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The
        <Bold>Use Beta Textures</Bold> checkbox switches the texture palette to use the
        texture pack from the May 5 prototype build of Urban Chaos rather than the final release
        version. This is useful if you want to recreate the visual style of earlier builds or
        experiment with the prototype's different texture set.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/textures_beta_checkbox.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Painting Textures
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To paint a texture onto the map, click on a texture in the palette to select it. Once
        selected, you will see two visual indicators on the canvas:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A
                <Bold>yellow highlight</Bold> around the tile currently under your cursor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A
                <Bold>ghost preview</Bold> of the selected texture beneath your cursor, showing you exactly what the tile will look like when placed.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/textures_ghost_preview.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph>
        Click on any tile to paint the selected texture onto it. The texture will immediately
        appear on the canvas.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Rotating Textures
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        While a texture is selected, you can rotate it before painting:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Press
                <Bold>Spacebar</Bold> to cycle through rotation angles.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use the
                <Bold>Rotation buttons</Bold> in the Textures tab to set a specific rotation.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The rotation arrow indicator in the palette shows the current direction of rotation,
        so you can see which way the texture will be oriented before placing it.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/textures_rotation.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Painting Multiple Tiles
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        There are several ways to paint textures across larger areas efficiently:
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Brush Size</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Adjust the brush size between 1 and 10 using the control in the
        Textures tab. A brush size of 1 paints a single tile (1x1), while a size of 10 paints a
        10x10 area with each click.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Click and Drag</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Click and drag across the canvas to paint a rectangular area in
        one motion. This is the fastest way to fill large regions with a single texture.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Stroke Painting (Shift+Click)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Hold
        <Bold>Shift</Bold> while clicking and moving the mouse to
        paint a continuous stroke along the path of your cursor. This is useful for painting
        roads, paths, and other linear features.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Finishing
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When you are finished painting,
        <Bold>right-click</Bold> anywhere on the canvas to
        deselect the current texture and clear the painting action. The ghost preview and
        yellow highlight will disappear, returning the cursor to its normal state.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Sampling a Texture from the Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you want to reuse a texture that is already painted somewhere on the map, you can
        sample it directly rather than hunting for it in the palette. This is done with the
        <Bold>Eye (sample) tool</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click the
                <Bold>Eye icon</Bold> in the Textures tab toolbar to enter sample mode.
                The cursor changes to indicate that the next map click will sample rather than paint.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click any tile on the map canvas. The texture on that tile is immediately
                <Bold>copied to the clipboard</Bold> and also becomes the active texture in the
                palette — ready to paint with straight away.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/textures_sampled.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph>
        Sample mode is a one-shot action — after the click the tool automatically returns to
        the normal paint tool so you can start painting immediately with the sampled texture.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Selecting an Area (Rectangle Select, Copy and Paste)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Select Area</Bold> tool lets you copy a rectangular block of existing map
        textures and paste them elsewhere — useful for duplicating patterns, mirroring sections,
        or moving a finished area to a new location.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Making a Selection
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Switch to the <Bold>Select</Bold> tool in the Textures tab, then click and drag on the
        map canvas to draw a rectangular selection. A dashed outline appears over the selected
        region as you drag.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/textures_select_area.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Copying the Selection
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once a rectangular area is selected, press
        <Bold>Ctrl+C</Bold> to copy all of the textures (and their rotations) within the
        selection to the clipboard. The selection outline remains visible so you can confirm
        the correct area was captured before pasting.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Pasting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Press <Bold>Ctrl+V</Bold> to enter paste mode. A
        <Bold>ghost preview</Bold> of the copied block appears under your cursor, showing
        exactly how the textures will land when placed. Move your cursor to the desired
        position and <Bold>click to place</Bold> the block.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Help/Images/textures_select_area_paste.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph>
        After placing, the ghost remains active so you can stamp the same block multiple times.
        Press <Bold>Escape</Bold> or <Bold>right-click</Bold> to cancel the paste and return
        to the normal tool.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2A3A" BorderBrush="#4A4A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#B0B0E0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>You can copy a selection and then immediately paste it into a different part of the map without leaving the Textures tab. The clipboard is also populated by the Eye sample tool, so sampling a single tile and then pressing Ctrl+V lets you stamp that one texture repeatedly as a 1×1 paste.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Worked Example
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In this example, we will paint a 5x5 tiled area using World 3 textures.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 1:</Bold> Open the Textures tab and enter
        <Bold>3</Bold> in the World box.
        The canvas populates with the default texture and the palette loads.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 2:</Bold> In the World Textures tab, scroll down and select
        <Bold>tex239hi</Bold> -- a tiled surface texture.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 3:</Bold> Move your cursor over the canvas. You will see the yellow highlight
        and ghost preview showing where the texture will be placed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 4:</Bold> Click and drag across a 5x5 area on the canvas. The texture is
        painted to all 25 tiles in the rectangle as you drag.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/textures_example_5x5.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,2">
        <Bold>Step 5:</Bold> Right-click to deselect the texture and finish painting.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Tips
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use the
                <Bold>Textures layer toggle</Bold> in the toolbar to show or hide the painted ground textures on the canvas.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Enable the
                <Bold>Grid layer</Bold> while painting to see the exact cell boundaries and ensure precise placement.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Zoom in with
                <Bold>Ctrl+Mouse Wheel</Bold> for finer control when painting detailed areas, and zoom out for broad coverage.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Shared textures (roads, sidewalks) are the same across all world numbers, so you can safely use them regardless of which world is selected.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Remember to
                <Bold>save your map</Bold> (Ctrl+S) after painting. Texture changes exist only in memory until saved.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Use the
                <Bold>Eye tool</Bold> to quickly grab a texture already on the map without scrolling through the palette to find it.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Ctrl+C / Ctrl+V</Bold> works on the current selection — copy a finished section of the map and paste it elsewhere to replicate patterns without repainting tile by tile.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
